    {
      "citation_id": "[CITATION_12]",
      "span_text": "Molecular genetic data were not available in the patients with LCA studied. LCA is currently diagnosed by history, clinical examination, and electrophysiological findings and there have been very few published studies of genotype-phenotype correlation in LCA. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] The FAF findings in this sample of patients with LCA suggest that they do not carry mutations, at least in MERTK or RPE65, because such genetic defects should cause extremely reduced FAF. There has been a preliminary report that patients with RPE65 mutations show absent or [CITATION_6] 63 or an inability of the RPE to recycle metabolites. [CITATION_7] 65 The high-density ring of FAF in the patient with RP (Fig. 2) resembled that in many other patients who manifest classic clinical signs of RP with preserved visual acuity. [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] 66 Pattern ERG studies in these patients demonstrate a high correlation between the size of the abnormal ring and the degree of macular dysfunction, suggesting that lipofuscin accumulates at the boundary between normal and severely abnormal retinal function. 54 Psychophysical studies based on high spatial resolution perimetry (fine matrix mapping) also suggest dramatically changing sensitivity across the width of the high-density ring and a profound reduction in sensitivity in the surrounding retinal areas. 66 Age-related differences in ring size have been described in an autosomal dominant pedigree of RP in patients with preserved central macular function, 54 and it has been suggested that the ring may demarcate the internal edge of peripheral field constriction as it encroaches on central macular areas, 54 consistent with progressive visual field loss in RP. [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] The functional significance of the high-density ring in patients with abnormal visual acuity is not known, but it is notable that the ring in patient C (Fig. 5) is approximately half the radius of that in her 15-year-old daughter (patient B; Fig.  4a ). It is tempting to speculate that, in these cases, the ring of high density may constrict with time, possibly indicating progressive or slowly changing metabolic disturbance that may occur without degeneration and in the presence of severe central visual impairment. Longitudinal studies are needed to investigate this proposal."
